subtitle: Goddess of Agriculture, Grain & Fertility
name: üåæCeres
summary: Also known as üåæ Ceres. Associated with agriculture, grain & fertility ceres, üåæ ceres, fertility.
extracted_lists: Fox Statues (Komainu): Pairs of fox statues flank Inari shrine entrances, typically holding symbolic objects - rice sheaves, keys, jewels, or scrolls in their mouths or under their paws.

Rice Granary Guardians: Foxes were historically seen as protectors of rice granaries because they hunt rats and mice that would otherwise eat stored grain, making them practical as well as symbolic guardians.
Intelligence   Magic: Kitsune represent cleverness, wisdom, and supernatural power. The longer a fox lives, the more tails it grows and the more powerful it becomes (up to nine tails).

Shapeshifters: Fox spirits can transform into human form, especially beautiful women, and this shapeshifting ability links them to transformation and change - essential agricultural concepts (seed to plant, harvest to food).
Agricultural Deity: Likely originated as a local agricultural kami worshipped by farming communities dependent on rice cultivation. The name "Inari" directly relates to rice growing/ripening.
Syncretism: May be a syncretic fusion of multiple earlier rice and fertility deities including Uke-Mochi (killed by Tsukuyomi, from whose body came rice), Toyouke-Hime, or Ukanomitama-no-Kami.
Hata Clan Origins: Tradition associates Inari worship with the Hata clan, Korean immigrants who brought advanced agricultural and silk production techniques to Japan in the 5th-6th centuries.
Mountain Deity: Fushimi Inari (the head shrine) sits on Mount Inari, suggesting possible origins as a mountain kami who descended to bless the rice fields in the valleys.
Buddhist Influence: During the medieval period, Inari was sometimes identified with Buddhist figures, especially Dakini-ten (a tantric deity), adding layers of complexity and esoteric meaning.
Red Torii Gates: Vermillion torii gates (often in long tunnels or rows) mark Inari shrines. Donors contribute these gates as offerings when wishes are granted.
Fox Statues: Pairs of fox guardians (sometimes holding rice, keys, or jewels) flank shrine entrances and dot the grounds.
Mountain Location: Many Inari shrines sit on or near mountains, with pilgrimage paths marked by countless torii gates.
Business Shrines: Small Inari shrines appear on rooftops and in businesses, especially in merchant districts, seeking prosperity.
Hatsu-Uma Festival (First Horse Day): Held on the first horse day of February (Inari's traditional descent date), this is the most important Inari festival celebrating the kami's blessing of crops.
Inari Matsuri: Various local festivals throughout the year, especially at planting and harvest times.
New Year (Shogatsu): Inari shrines receive massive crowds seeking blessings for prosperity in the coming year.

name: Cupido Amor

family.siblings: Anteros (Requited Love), Himeros (Longing), Pothos (Yearning) - the Erotes

summary: Also known as Cupido Amor. Associated with unknown.

search.searchableText: cupido amor cupido amor cupido amor

extracted_lists: Apollo and Daphne: When Apollo mocked Cupid's archery, the god of love took revenge. He shot Apollo with a golden arrow, causing him to fall desperately in love with the nymph Daphne. He shot Daphne with a lead arrow, filling her with aversion. Daphne fled and was transformed into a laurel tree to escape Apollo's pursuit (Ovid, Metamorphoses I).

The Arrows of Love: Cupid possesses two types of arrows: golden-tipped arrows kindle irresistible passion, while lead-tipped arrows cause disgust and flight from love. Even Jupiter is not immune to Cupid's power‚Äîmany of his famous affairs were sparked by Cupid's intervention.

The Blindfolded God: Later traditions depicted Cupid blindfolded, representing that love is blind and strikes without regard for social standing, wisdom, or consequence. This image influenced the Renaissance and modern depictions of "blind love."
Venus's Weapon: As Venus 's son and constant companion, Cupid often acted as her instrument, inflaming passion to reward devotees or punish those who offended her.
Mother: Venus (most common tradition)
Father: Mars (most common tradition), or Mercury , or Vulcan (various accounts)
Wife: Psyche (Soul), the mortal princess made divine
Daughter: Voluptas (Pleasure), born to Cupid and Psyche
Siblings: Anteros (Requited Love), Himeros (Longing), Pothos (Yearning) - the Erotes
Weddings: Cupid blessed marriages and was invoked at wedding ceremonies for lasting love
Lupercalia (February 15): This fertility festival, later associated with Valentine's Day, had connections to love's divine power
Venus Festivals: Cupid was honored alongside his mother during the Veneralia (April 1) and other Venus celebrations
Dual Arrows: The Roman tradition of golden and leaden arrows (love and aversion) is more developed than in Greek sources
Psyche Tale: The elaborate Cupid and Psyche narrative is a Roman literary creation (Apuleius), not found in Greek myth
Mischievous Child: Roman art and poetry often emphasized Cupid as a playful, naughty child-god, while Greek Eros could be a powerful primordial force
Venus's Agent: Roman sources frequently depict Cupid as Venus's obedient (or disobedient) son and tool, less as an independent cosmic power
Blindfolded Love: The image of blind Cupid became particularly prominent in Roman and later European tradition
Elegiac Poetry: Roman love poets (Ovid, Propertius, Tibullus) made Cupid a central figure in their amatory verse
